13:34.813 --> 13:36.513
James, what happened to you?

14:07.245 --> 14:08.946
Hello?

14:14.719 --> 14:16.086
Hello?

14:28.333 --> 14:29.399
Henry Cale?
Yes.

14:29.401 --> 14:33.203
We spoke on the phone.
Hi. I'm Anne Roland.

14:33.205 --> 14:37.040
So tell me everything you know
about shortwave radio broadcasts.

14:37.042 --> 14:39.276
Yeah. Well, I'm an operator
and enthusiast,

14:39.278 --> 14:41.645
and I've been working with
it all my life. Come here.

14:50.855 --> 14:52.122
I don't like this.

14:52.124 --> 14:53.523
We should call someone.

14:53.525 --> 14:55.125
I ingested the chemical, remember?

14:55.127 --> 14:56.627
I took that. We don't...

14:58.464 --> 15:00.898
- Oh, fuck, Renny.
- What?

15:00.900 --> 15:03.533
It's coming towards the house.

15:04.970 --> 15:08.005
Yeah, that sound on the radio

15:08.007 --> 15:12.042
sounds exactly like one
of the known numbers stations.

15:12.044 --> 15:13.477
Numbers stations?

15:15.079 --> 15:18.949
Numbers stations are shortwave radio
stations of unidentified origin.

15:18.951 --> 15:22.552
They generally broadcast
artificially generated voices

15:22.554 --> 15:26.290
reading streams of numbers,
words, letters,

15:26.292 --> 15:30.127
backwards music,
or cryptic electronic code.

15:30.129 --> 15:32.529
They're in a wide
variety of languages,

15:32.531 --> 15:36.767
and the voices are usually
female for some reason.

15:36.769 --> 15:40.270
Sometimes it sounds like a child.

15:40.272 --> 15:42.472
And how long have you been
hearing them for?

15:42.474 --> 15:44.174
Well, the shortwave community's

15:44.176 --> 15:45.943
been finding them for decades now.

15:45.945 --> 15:47.744
Listen.

15:49.581 --> 15:54.584
7, 5, 4, 6, 8.

16:00.391 --> 16:04.394
8, 7, 7, 6, 5.

16:24.682 --> 16:27.417
Who would broadcast that?

16:27.419 --> 16:30.153
Lot of theories...
secret government agencies,

16:30.155 --> 16:31.955
terrorists, drug runners.

16:31.957 --> 16:34.024
But it's never been shown for sure

16:34.026 --> 16:35.959
who or what is broadcasting them.

16:35.961 --> 16:39.363
So you've been keeping track
of these numbers stations

16:39.365 --> 16:40.931
and documenting them for years?

16:40.933 --> 16:42.532
That's right.

16:42.534 --> 16:44.701
And you've heard that
particular broadcast before?

16:44.703 --> 16:46.370
Yes, I have.

16:49.340 --> 16:51.408
The signal sounded like a
broadcast from this small area

16:51.410 --> 16:53.710
we call the Lonely Traveler Station.

16:53.712 --> 16:55.545
The Lonely Traveler?

16:55.547 --> 16:57.148
Yeah. Shortwave radio
guys named it that.

16:57.149 --> 16:58.882
I've heard recordings,

16:58.884 --> 17:02.452
but I've never gone out there
to listen to it myself.

17:02.454 --> 17:05.622
Well, James's cabin
is right about here,

17:05.624 --> 17:07.656
same area upstate.

17:07.659 --> 17:10.627
So what do I need to do if I
wanted to record this broadcast?

17:10.628 --> 17:12.128
Well, it's not easy.

17:12.131 --> 17:15.365
You'd need to be out on the far
edge of the Black Rock Desert

17:15.367 --> 17:17.233
between 3:00 to 5:00
in the morning,

17:17.236 --> 17:19.669
and maybe cross your fingers.

17:19.671 --> 17:21.204
That's it?

17:21.205 --> 17:22.939
Doesn't sound so bad.

17:22.941 --> 17:24.074
Yeah, that's it.

17:24.076 --> 17:26.542
I can give you one of our receivers.

17:26.545 --> 17:27.743
One more question.

17:27.746 --> 17:30.614
Did you... Did you used
to work for the NSA?

17:30.616 --> 17:33.617
Excuse me?
You know, the NSA.

17:33.619 --> 17:35.819
You worked for them
as a code breaker.

17:35.821 --> 17:37.788
